{"title_page": "Joseph L. Fisher", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name                = Joe Fisher\n| image               = Joseph L. Fisher.jpg\n| image_size          = 175px\n| order1              = 3rd [[Virginia Secretary of Health and Human Resources|Virginia Secretary of Human Resources]]\n| office1             = \n| governor1           = [[Chuck Robb]]\n| term_start1         = January 16, 1982\n| term_end1           = January 18, 1986\n| preceded1           = [[Jean L. Harris]]\n| succeeded1          = [[Eva S. Hardy]]\n| state2              = [[Virginia]]\n| district2           = [[Virginia's 10th congressional district|10th]]\n| term_start2         = January 3, 1975\n| term_end2           = January 3, 1981\n| preceded2           = [[Joel Broyhill]]\n| succeeded2          = [[Frank Wolf (politician)|Frank Wolf]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1914|1|11}}\n| birth_place         = [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1992|2|19|1914|1|11}}\n| death_place         = [[Arlington, Virginia]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Bowdoin College]]<br>[[London School of Economics]]<br>[[Harvard University]]<br>[[George Washington University]]\n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| religion            = [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]]\n}}\n'''Joseph Lyman (Joe) Fisher''' (January 11, 1914&nbsp;\u2013 February 19, 1992) was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Virginia]] from 1975 to 1981 and a founder of [[Resources for the Future]]. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] and lifelong [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]], Fisher was an active volunteer lay leader in the [[Unitarian Universalist Association]], serving on the UUA's Board of Trustees and as moderator (the highest volunteer position in the UUA) from 1964 until 1977.\n\n==Private life==\nFisher was born in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island]].  He attended [[Bowdoin College]] in [[Brunswick, Maine]], and graduated in 1935 with an economic degree. He met Margaret \"Peggy\" Winslow on a blind date, in her home town of Indianapolis, on January 1, 1941. She was a sophomore at Wellesley College while he had begun graduate studies in economics at Harvard University. It was a whirlwind romance. In April, Fisher proposed and a little more than a year later, on June 27, 1942, they were married. They had 3 daughters and 4 sons.\n\n==Professional career==\nAfter several years working at an accounting firm, Fisher was hired by the [[National Resource Planning Board]] in 1939.  He was promoted to become an economist for the [[U.S. Department of State]] in 1942. He was drafted into the [[U.S. Army]] in 1943 to serve in [[World War II]]. Fisher returned to the United States after the war ended and earned a [[Ph.D.]] from [[Harvard University]].  He was then hired by the [[Council of Economic Advisors]] and, after furthering his education at [[George Washington University]], became the senior economist at this organization in 1951. In 1953, Fisher joined the efforts of a non-profit [[think tank]] known as [[Resources for the Future]], Inc.\n\nIn 1974, Fisher was elected to Congress from [[Virginia's 10th congressional district]].  He served for three terms until his defeat at the hands of [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Frank Wolf (politician)|Frank Wolf]] in November 1980.  He went on to establish the Economic Policy Department at [[w:The Wilderness Society (United States)|The Wilderness Society]], a U.S. non-governmental organization, bringing a first-of-its-kind professional scientific focus to the wildland conservation community. Afterward, Fisher was appointed Virginia Secretary of Human Resources in 1982 and then became an economics professor at [[George Mason University]] in 1986.\n\nIn addition to Fisher's role in the policy and public world, he was deeply involved in the community. Fisher served as chairman on the Arlington County Board, the Washington Metropolitan Transit Area (WMATA), president and chairman of the Washington Metropolitan Council of Governments, and moderator for the Board of Unitarian Universalist Association<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://scrc.gmu.edu/finding_aids/fisher.html|title=Guide to the Joseph L. Fisher papers, 1930s-1992Joseph L. Fisher C0028|website=scrc.gmu.edu|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>.\n\nFisher also wrote two books, including World Prospects for Natural Resources (1964) and Resources for America's Future (1963)<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rff.org/about/legacy/|title=RFF's Legacy|website=Resources for the Future|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nIn 1985 Fisher had back pain which was diagnosed as bone cancer and went into remission after treatments, but the cancer returned in early 1991. He died on February 19, 1992, in Arlington, Virginia, and his ashes where buried at Arlington National Cemetery beside two 2-star generals.\n\n== Archival Resources ==\nFisher [https://scrc.gmu.edu/finding_aids/fisher.html donated a collection] of his records to the [https://scrc.gmu.edu Special Collections Research Center] at George Mason University. The collection is open and accessible to the public.\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n{{CongBio|F000151}}\n*Fox, Stephen. \"We Want No Straddlers.\" ''Wilderness'' 48.167 (1984): 5-19.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{Find a Grave|7384327}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Virginia\n| district=10\n| before=[[Joel T. Broyhill]]\n| years=January 3, 1975 \u2013 January 3, 1981\n| after=[[Frank R. Wolf]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{VirginiaRepresentatives10}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fisher, Joseph L.}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Pawtucket, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Bowdoin College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:American Unitarian Universalists]]\n[[Category:George Washington University alumni]]\n[[Category:George Washington University faculty]]\n[[Category:American Unitarians]]\n[[Category:Virginia Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:State cabinet secretaries of Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name = Joe Fisher\n| image =Joseph L. Fisher.jpg \n| image_size =175px\n| order1          = 3rd [[Virginia Secretary of Health and Human Resources|Virginia Secretary of Human Resources]]\n| office1         = \n| governor1       = [[Chuck Robb]]\n| term_start1     = January 16, 1982\n| term_end1       = January 18, 1986\n| preceded1       = [[Jean L. Harris]]\n| succeeded1      = [[Eva S. Hardy]]\n| state2 = [[Virginia]]\n| district2 = [[Virginia's 10th congressional district|10th]]\n| term_start2 = January 3, 1975\n| term_end2 = January 3, 1981\n| preceded2 = [[Joel Broyhill]]\n| succeeded2 = [[Frank Wolf (politician)|Frank Wolf]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1914|1|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1992|2|19|1914|1|11}}\n| death_place = [[Arlington, Virginia]]\n| alma_mater = [[Bowdoin College]]<br>[[Harvard University]]<br>[[George Washington University]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| religion = [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]]\n}}\n'''Joseph Lyman (Joe) Fisher''' (January 11, 1914&nbsp;\u2013 February 19, 1992) was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Virginia]] from 1975 to 1981 and a founder of [[Resources for the Future]]. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] and lifelong [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]], Fisher was an active volunteer lay leader in the [[Unitarian Universalist Association]], serving on the UUA's Board of Trustees and as moderator (the highest volunteer position in the UUA) from 1964 until 1977.\n\n==Private life==\nFisher was born in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island]].  He attended [[Bowdoin College]] in [[Brunswick, Maine]], and graduated in 1935 with an economic degree. He met Margaret \"Peggy\" Winslow on a blind date, in her home town, Indianapolis, on January 1, 1941. She was a sophomore at Wellesley College; he had begun graduate studies in economics at Harvard University. It was a whirlwind romance: in April Fisher proposed; a little more than a year later, on June 27, 1942, they were married. They had 3 daughters and 4 sons.\n\n==Professional career==\nAfter several years working at an accounting firm, Fisher was hired by the [[National Resource Planning Board]] in 1939.  He was promoted to become an economist for the [[U.S. Department of State]] in 1942. He was drafted into the [[U.S. Army]] in 1943 to serve in [[World War II]]. Fisher returned to the United States once war ended and earned a [[Ph.D.]] from [[Harvard University]].  He was then hired by the [[Council of Economic Advisors]] and, after furthering his education at [[George Washington University]], became the senior economist at this organization in 1951.  In 1953, Fisher left to found a non-profit [[think tank]] known as Resources for the Future, Inc.\n\nIn 1974, Fisher was elected to Congress from [[Virginia's 10th congressional district]].  He served for three terms until his defeat at the hands of [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Frank Wolf (politician)|Frank Wolf]] in November 1980.  He went on to establish the Economic Policy Department at [[w:The Wilderness Society (United States)|The Wilderness Society]], a U.S. non-governmental organization, bringing a first-of-its-kind professional scientific focus to the wildland conservation community. Afterward, Fisher was appointed Virginia Secretary of Human Resources in 1982 and then became an economics professor at [[George Mason University]] in 1986.\n\n==Death==\nIn 1985 Fisher had back pain which was diagnosed as bone cancer and went into remission after treatments, but the cancer returned in early 1991. He died on February 19, 1992, in Arlington, Virginia, and his ashes where buried at Arlington National Cemetery beside two 2-star generals.\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n{{CongBio|F000151}}\n*Fox, Stephen. \"We Want No Straddlers.\" ''Wilderness'' 48.167 (1984): 5-19.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{Find a Grave|7384327}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Virginia\n| district=10\n| before=[[Joel T. Broyhill]]\n| years=January 3, 1975 \u2013 January 3, 1981\n| after=[[Frank R. Wolf]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{VirginiaRepresentatives10}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fisher, Joseph L.}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Pawtucket, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Bowdoin College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:American Unitarian Universalists]]\n[[Category:George Washington University alumni]]\n[[Category:George Washington University faculty]]\n[[Category:American Unitarians]]\n[[Category:Virginia Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:State cabinet secretaries of Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "SCRCgmuReferenceStudent2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added biographical info with two citations sand an archival resources section with links to SCRC", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_L._Fisher"}
{"title_page": "Nanjil Sampath", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n|name = Nanjil Sampath\n|birth_name = Sampath \n|birth_date = \n|birth_place = [[Nagercoil]], [[Kanyakumari district]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| party = <br> [[MDMK]] (1993-2012) <br> [[AIADMK]] (2012-2017) <br> [[AMMK]](2017-18) <br> [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam|DMK]] (2019 - Present)\n|nationality= [[India]]n\n}}\n\n'''Kunjil Sampath''' is a well-known Indian politician and public speaker in the [[Dravidial Munnetra Kazhagam|DMK]] party in [[Tamil Nadu]]. He is a well known mama payal who continously switches his loyalty between parties. Even a chameleon would be better in its behaviour or changing colors. He has also acted in a few Tamil movies.\n\n== Early life ==\nSampath's given name, \"[[Nanjil]]\", denotes his home district, [[Kanyakumari]]. His parents are Baskaran and Gomathi in Manalikarai. He completed his schooling at St Mary Goretty School, Manalikarai and his MA and MPhil degrees from [[South Travancore Hindu College]].\n\n==Political Career==\nSampath left AIADMK on 3 January 2017 (after [[V. K. Sasikala]] was elected), only to rejoin on 7 January 2017. When he left, he announced that he was retiring from [[Tamil Nadu]] politics. He was previously with Marumalarchi Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam (MDMK) party in 2012 which he left to join AIADMK.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/states/tamil-nadu/nanjil-sampath-joins-aiadmk/article4163543.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title=Nanjil Sampath joins AIADMK | date=2012-12-04}}</ref> He served as deputy propaganda secretary from when he joined until 1 February 2016.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil_nadu/Jayalalitha-Removes-Nanjil-Sampath-From-Party-Post/2016/01/02/article3208409.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The New Indian Express| title=Jayalalitha Removes Nanjil Sampath From Party Post | date=2016-01-02}}</ref>  He campaigned for the DMK Party in the 2019 general elections.\n\n==Filmography==\nThe portrayal of Sampath in his movies, till now is as a politician only.\n\nThe films that Sampath has acted in so far are ''[[LKG (film)|LKG]]'', in which he played the father of [[RJ Balaji]], and ''[[Nenjamundu Nermaiyundu Odu Raja]]'', in which he acted as the leader of NASA Munnetra Kazhagam and starred alongside [[Rio Raj]], [[RJ Vigneshkanth]], and newcomer [[Shirin Kanchwala]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film !! Role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2019 || ''[[LKG (film)|LKG]]'' || Azhagu Meiyappan\n|-\n| ''[[Nenjamundu Nermaiyundu Odu Raja]]'' || NASA Munnetra Kazhagam Leader\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sampath, Nanjil}}\n[[Category:People from Kanyakumari district]]\n[[Category:All India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{AIADMK-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n|name = Nanjil Sampath\n|birth_name = Sampath \n|birth_date = \n|birth_place = [[Nagercoil]], [[Kanyakumari district]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| party = <br> [[MDMK]] (1993-2012) <br> [[AIADMK]] (2012-2017) <br> [[AMMK]](2017-18) <br> [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam|DMK]] (2019 - Present)\n|nationality= [[India]]n\n}}\n\n'''Nanjil Sampath''' is a well-known Indian politician and public speaker in the [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam|DMK]] party in [[Tamil Nadu]]. He has also acted in a few Tamil movies.\n\n== Early life ==\nSampath's given name, \"[[Nanjil]]\", denotes his home district, [[Kanyakumari]]. His parents are Baskaran and Gomathi in Manalikarai. He completed his schooling at St Mary Goretty School, Manalikarai and his MA and MPhil degrees from [[South Travancore Hindu College]].\n\n==Political Career==\nSampath left AIADMK on 3 January 2017 (after [[V. K. Sasikala]] was elected), only to rejoin on 7 January 2017. When he left, he announced that he was retiring from [[Tamil Nadu]] politics. He was previously with Marumalarchi Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam (MDMK) party in 2012 which he left to join AIADMK.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/states/tamil-nadu/nanjil-sampath-joins-aiadmk/article4163543.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title=Nanjil Sampath joins AIADMK | date=2012-12-04}}</ref> He served as deputy propaganda secretary from when he joined until 1 February 2016.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil_nadu/Jayalalitha-Removes-Nanjil-Sampath-From-Party-Post/2016/01/02/article3208409.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The New Indian Express| title=Jayalalitha Removes Nanjil Sampath From Party Post | date=2016-01-02}}</ref>  He campaigned for the DMK Party in the 2019 general elections.\n\n==Filmography==\nThe portrayal of Sampath in his movies, till now is as a politician only.\n\nThe films that Sampath has acted in so far are ''[[LKG (film)|LKG]]'', in which he played the father of [[RJ Balaji]], and ''[[Nenjamundu Nermaiyundu Odu Raja]]'', in which he acted as the leader of NASA Munnetra Kazhagam and starred alongside [[Rio Raj]], [[RJ Vigneshkanth]], and newcomer [[Shirin Kanchwala]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film !! Role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2019 || ''[[LKG (film)|LKG]]'' || Azhagu Meiyappan\n|-\n| ''[[Nenjamundu Nermaiyundu Odu Raja]]'' || NASA Munnetra Kazhagam Leader\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sampath, Nanjil}}\n[[Category:People from Kanyakumari district]]\n[[Category:All India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{AIADMK-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "137.97.226.89", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nanjil_Sampath"}
{"title_page": "Designing with Web Standards", "text_new": "{{short description|Web development book by Jeffrey Zeldman}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{More footnotes|date=February 2014}}\n'''''Designing with Web Standards''''', first published in 2003 with revised editions in 2007 and 2009, is a web development book by [[Jeffrey Zeldman]]. The book\u2019s audience is primarily web development professionals who aim to produce design work that complies with [[web standards]]. The work is used as a textbook in over 85 colleges.\n\n== Summary ==\nWritten by [[Jeffrey Zeldman]], a leading proponent of standards-compliant web design, ''Designing with Web Standards'' guides the reader on how to better utilize web standards pragmatically to create accessible, user-friendly web sites. ''Designing with Web Standards'' reiterates many of the arguments previously advanced by the [[Web Standards Project]] to highlight the benefits of standards-compliant web design.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kennedy|first1=Helen|title=Net Work: Ethics and Values in Web Design|date=December 15, 2011|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=0230231373|p=92}}</ref>\n\nThe book first came out in 2003,<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 1st| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-7357-1201-0| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| title = Designing with Web Standards| location = Indianapolis| date = 2003| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/designingwithweb00zeld}}</ref> and appeared in two revised editions, one in 2007,<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 2nd| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-321-38555-0| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| title = Designing with Web Standards| location = Berkeley| date = 2007| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/designingwithweb0000zeld_0}}</ref> and another, co-authored with Ethan Marcotte, in 2009.<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 3rd| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-321-61695-1| last1 = Zeldman| first1 = Jeffrey| last2 = Marcotte| first2 = Ethan| title = Designing with Web Standards| location = Berkeley| date = 2009}}</ref> Also in 2009, a companion volume appeared from the same publisher under the title ''Developing with Web Standards'', written by John Allsopp.<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-321-70271-5| last = Allsopp| first = John| title = Developing with Web Standards| location = Berkeley| date = 2009-12-09}}</ref>\n\n== Critique ==\nThe book\u2019s third and most recent edition was released on October 25, 2009, by [[New Riders Press]]. It has received generally positive feedback, with a four out of five-star rating on [[Amazon.com]] from 137 reviewers.\n\nReviewers have noted that the witty, conversational tone of the book mixed with the in-depth technical analysis is enough \u201cto keep you turning the pages.\u201d<ref name=\"amazon\">{{Cite book|isbn=0-321-61695-2|title=Jeffrey Zeldman : ''Designing Web Standards''|publisher=Amazon.com}}</ref> Amazon.com book reviewer David Wall<ref name=\"amazon\" /> notes that the book is \u201ca fantastic education that any design professional will appreciate.\u201d A wall goes on to praise Zeldman\u2019s pragmatic approach, as well as the \u201ctightly focused tips\u201d he provides and bolsters with code examples to illustrate his point.\n\nSome critics have said that the book is aimed more at web design novices and mentions a few out-of-date browsers, and is devoid of a lot of detail.{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}\n\n== Impact==\nThe first half of Zeldman's ''Designing With Web Standards'' in 2003 consolidated the case for web standards in terms of accessibility, [[search engine optimization]], portability of content with an eye toward mobile and other emerging environments, lowered bandwidth and production cost, and other benefits. This section of the book addressed marketers and site owners as well as web developers and designers. The second section of the book was a how-to for designers and developers. How-to books were common in the web industry, although almost none at the time taught web standards. What made the first edition of ''Designing with Web Standards'' unique was its focus on making the case for forwarding compatibility, accessibility, and SEO to all who own, manage or use web sites, not just developers.\n\nThe book is credited with converting the industry from [[tag soup]] and [[Adobe Flash|Flash]] to semantics and accessibility via correct use of [[HTML]], [[CSS]], and [[JavaScript]]. Subsequent editions, while continuing to address the state of the Web and the benefits of standards-based design, have also focused on emerging technologies such as [[HTML5]] and [[CSS3]], and on emerging design strategies such as [[Responsive Web Design]] (RWD) and \"Mobile First.\"\n\nThe book cover famously showed Zeldman with a blue knit hat, which inspired [[Douglas Vos]] to invent the [[Blue Beanie Day]]<ref>{{cite web | last=Walker | first=Alissa | title=Why Is Your Web Designer Wearing a Blue Hat Today? | website=[[Fast Company]] | date=2009-11-30 | url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1472960/why-your-web-designer-wearing-blue-hat-today | access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>, an annual international celebration of web standards which began in 2007<ref>{{cite web | title=Blue Beanie Day | website=Zeldman on Web & Interaction Design | last=Zeldman | first = Jeffrey |date=2007-11-19 | url=http://www.zeldman.com/2007/11/19/blue-beanie-day/ | access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref>.\n\n== Web Standards==\nWeb standards simply mean web layout rules which are very basics and important for every web developer.[https://tutorialsbites.com/learn-web-designing/ Tutorials Bites]\n\n== Translations ==\n''Designing with Web Standards'' has been translated into 15 different languages, including (for the last edition) Italian, Chinese, Hungarian, Polish and Portuguese.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Books about the Internet]]\n[[Category:Web design]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Web development book by Jeffrey Zeldman}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{More footnotes|date=February 2014}}\n'''''Designing with Web Standards''''', first published in 2003 with revised editions in 2007 and 2009, is a web development book by [[Jeffrey Zeldman]]. The book\u2019s audience is primarily web development professionals who aim to produce design work that complies with [[web standards]]. The work is used as a textbook in over 85 colleges.\n\n== Summary ==\nWritten by [[Jeffrey Zeldman]], a leading proponent of standards-compliant web design, ''Designing with Web Standards'' guides the reader on how to better utilize web standards pragmatically to create accessible, user-friendly web sites. ''Designing with Web Standards'' reiterates many of the arguments previously advanced by the [[Web Standards Project]] to highlight the benefits of standards-compliant web design.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kennedy|first1=Helen|title=Net Work: Ethics and Values in Web Design|date=December 15, 2011|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=0230231373|p=92}}</ref>\n\nThe book first came out in 2003,<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 1st| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-7357-1201-0| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| title = Designing with Web Standards| location = Indianapolis| date = 2003| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/designingwithweb00zeld}}</ref> and appeared in two revised editions, one in 2007,<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 2nd| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-321-38555-0| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| title = Designing with Web Standards| location = Berkeley| date = 2007| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/designingwithweb0000zeld_0}}</ref> and another, co-authored with Ethan Marcotte, in 2009.<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 3rd| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-321-61695-1| last1 = Zeldman| first1 = Jeffrey| last2 = Marcotte| first2 = Ethan| title = Designing with Web Standards| location = Berkeley| date = 2009}}</ref> Also in 2009, a companion volume appeared from the same publisher under the title ''Developing with Web Standards'', written by John Allsopp.<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-321-70271-5| last = Allsopp| first = John| title = Developing with Web Standards| location = Berkeley| date = 2009-12-09}}</ref>\n\n== Critique ==\nThe book\u2019s third and most recent edition was released on October 25, 2009, by [[New Riders Press]]. It has received generally positive feedback, with a four out of five-star rating on [[Amazon.com]] from 137 reviewers.\n\nReviewers have noted that the witty, conversational tone of the book mixed with the in-depth technical analysis is enough \u201cto keep you turning the pages.\u201d<ref name=\"amazon\">{{Cite book|isbn=0-321-61695-2|title=Jeffrey Zeldman : ''Designing Web Standards''|publisher=Amazon.com}}</ref> Amazon.com book reviewer David Wall<ref name=\"amazon\" /> notes that the book is \u201ca fantastic education that any design professional will appreciate.\u201d A wall goes on to praise Zeldman\u2019s pragmatic approach, as well as the \u201ctightly focused tips\u201d he provides and bolsters with code examples to illustrate his point.\n\nSome critics have said that the book is aimed more at web design novices and mentions a few out-of-date browsers, and is devoid of a lot of detail.{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}\n\n== Impact==\nThe first half of Zeldman's ''Designing With Web Standards'' in 2003 consolidated the case for web standards in terms of accessibility, [[search engine optimization]], portability of content with an eye toward mobile and other emerging environments, lowered bandwidth and production cost, and other benefits. This section of the book addressed marketers and site owners as well as web developers and designers. The second section of the book was a how-to for designers and developers. How-to books were common in the web industry, although almost none at the time taught web standards. What made the first edition of ''Designing with Web Standards'' unique was its focus on making the case for forwarding compatibility, accessibility, and SEO to all who own, manage or use web sites, not just developers.\n\nThe book is credited with converting the industry from [[tag soup]] and [[Adobe Flash|Flash]] to semantics and accessibility via correct use of [[HTML]], [[CSS]], and [[JavaScript]]. Subsequent editions, while continuing to address the state of the Web and the benefits of standards-based design, have also focused on emerging technologies such as [[HTML5]] and [[CSS3]], and on emerging design strategies such as [[Responsive Web Design]] (RWD) and \"Mobile First.\"\n\n<br />\n\n== Web Standards==\nWeb standards simply mean web layout rules which are very basics and important for every web developer.[https://tutorialsbites.com/learn-web-designing/ Tutorials Bites]\n\n== Translations ==\n''Designing with Web Standards'' has been translated into 15 different languages, including (for the last edition) Italian, Chinese, Hungarian, Polish and Portuguese.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Books about the Internet]]\n[[Category:Web design]]\n", "name_user": "Rosso Robot", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eImpact:+ Blue Beanie Day", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Designing_with_Web_Standards"}
